What Is a Decision? (How Humans Choose vs Computers)

Every day, you make hundreds of decisions without even noticing. You decide when to wake up, what to eat, which road to take, or when to stop crossing a street. Most of the time, no one gives you a rulebook for these choices. You look at the situation, remember past experiences, and choose what feels right. This is what a decision really is — choosing one option over another based on what you know, what you see, and what you’ve learned before.

Now let’s think about how a computer makes a decision. When a computer chooses something, it doesn’t “feel” or “judge” the situation. It follows instructions. For example, a calculator decides the answer to “2 + 2” by following fixed steps written inside it. A traffic light decides to turn red when a timer ends, even if no cars are around. These are decisions too, but they are very different. The computer doesn’t understand why it is choosing — it is simply following instructions.

This is where humans and computers clearly differ. Humans can make decisions even when the situation is new or unclear. If it suddenly starts raining, you decide to slow down, take shelter, or use an umbrella — even if no one taught you a rule for that exact moment. Your brain connects memories, emotions, and context. Computers struggle here. If a situation is not mentioned in their instructions, they don’t know what to do unless someone updates the rules.

To make computers handle more situations, we started teaching them in a different way. Instead of writing rules for every possible choice, we show them many examples of decisions and their outcomes. Over time, the computer begins to notice patterns, like “this kind of situation usually leads to that kind of result.” This is similar to how a child learns. You don’t explain every possible danger — the child learns by seeing, trying, and adjusting after mistakes. The computer’s decisions slowly improve as it sees more examples.

So here’s the key idea to remember. Humans make decisions by understanding situations and adapting to them, even when things are new. Computers make decisions by following instructions or patterns learned from examples. They don’t truly understand the situation — they calculate the most likely choice based on what they’ve seen before. In the next part of this series, we’ll look at how this example-based decision-making works in more detail, and how machines actually learn from data.


